Some may say "Wal-Mart: A History of Sam Walton's Retail Phenomenon" by Sandra  Vance and Roy Scott profiles the American Dream.
Walton became one of the world's  most successful businessmen, leaving the second-largest fortune in the world.
Most  phenomenal was the rapid growth of the company, going from 38 stores to the largest in  America in 20 years.
This scholarly work identifies Wal-Mart's ability to copy and  adapt, staying open to new technology, and building the most efficient retail distribution  system.
It highlights the streamlined, rapidly responding, management and includes the  debate on whether Wal-Mart's impact on small towns was positive or negative. 
